<span id="freeTextContainer4667104183298719477">Lewis is brilliant! Here&apos;s a quote from the book that&apos;s never left my head:<br/><br/>&quot;I am trying here to prevent anyone saying the really foolish thing that people often say about Him: &apos;I&apos;m ready to accept Jesus as a great moral teacher, but I don&apos;t accept His claim to be God.&apos; That is the one thing we must not say. A man who was merely a man and said the sort of things Jesus said would not be a great moral teacher. He would either be a lunatic - on the level with the man who says he is a poached egg - o</span>
  <span id="freeText4667104183298719477" style="display:none">Lewis is brilliant! Here's a quote from the book that's never left my head:<br /><br />"I am trying here to prevent anyone saying the really foolish thing that people often say about Him: 'I'm ready to accept Jesus as a great moral teacher, but I don't accept His claim to be God.' That is the one thing we must not say. A man who was merely a man and said the sort of things Jesus said would not be a great moral teacher. He would either be a lunatic - on the level with the man who says he is a poached egg - or else he would be the Devil of Hell. You must make your choice. Either this man was, and is, the Son of God: or else a madman or something worse. You can shut Him up for a fool, you can spit at Him and kill Him as a demon; or you can fall at His feet and call Him Lord and God. But let us not come with any patronising nonsense about His being a great human teacher. He has not left that open to us. He did not intend to." (C.S. Lewis, Mere Christianity, The MacMillan Company, 1960, pp. 40-41.)</span>
